{"id":"project-LICHEN-e4so","title":"Missing validation that decoded and encrypted fields are mutually exclusive","description":"File: lichen/subsys/lichen/meshtastic/adapter.c:864-880

In parse_packet, both MESH_PACKET_DECODED_FIELD and MESH_PACKET_ENCRYPTED_FIELD are handled:

  case MESH_PACKET_DECODED_FIELD:
      if (wt != PB_WT_LEN || pb_read_len_value(&cur, &data, &data_len) < 0) {
          return -EINVAL;
      }
      if (parse_data(data, data_len, info) < 0) {
          return -EINVAL;
      }
      break;
  case MESH_PACKET_ENCRYPTED_FIELD:
      if (wt != PB_WT_LEN || pb_read_len_value(&cur, &data, &data_len) < 0) {
          return -EINVAL;
      }
      info->kind = LICHEN_MESHTASTIC_ADAPTER_PACKET_UNSUPPORTED;
      info->portnum = 0U;
      info->payload = NULL;
      info->payload_len = 0U;
      break;

Per Meshtastic protocol, a MeshPacket should have EITHER decoded OR encrypted, not both. If a malformed packet contains both fields, the last one in wire order wins (standard protobuf behavior).

Consider:
1. Tracking which field was seen first
2. Rejecting packets with both fields as MALFORMED
3. Or documenting that last-wins is intentional for forward compatibility","status":"open","priority":3,"issue_type":"bug","owner":"me@mark.atwood.name","created_at":"2026-07-12T06:50:17.42024Z","created_by":"Mark Atwood","updated_at":"2026-07-12T06:50:17.420278Z"}

